00:01:41.300 --> 00:01:45.500
So last week on "Android Design
in Action," we gave

00:01:45.500 --> 00:01:49.610
kind of a mission, a challenge
to the community to take an

00:01:49.610 --> 00:01:54.200
app that you've seen before and
potentially that you maybe

00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:56.220
don't like the layout
for and rethink

00:01:56.220 --> 00:01:58.020
it, redesign it yourself.

00:01:58.020 --> 00:02:02.310
Use your Photoshop skills, use
your sketching skills and put

00:02:02.310 --> 00:02:04.910
up a public redesign
of that app.

00:02:04.910 --> 00:02:06.490
And we've gotten a lot
of contestants--

00:02:06.490 --> 00:02:09.160
well, actually not really
contestants, a lot of entries.

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:12.620
And we're going to take a look
at some of those today as well

00:02:12.620 --> 00:02:16.220
as talk about VIA, the tablet
UI stencils that we promised

00:02:16.220 --> 00:02:17.850
to give away before.

00:02:17.850 --> 00:02:22.480
So let's get started and jump
into instant messaging.

00:02:22.480 --> 00:02:28.610
So rather than take a look at
existing apps like GroupMe and

00:02:28.610 --> 00:02:31.200
Trillion that were covered in
last week's App Clinic, we

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:35.080
wanted to think of what would
a hypothetical, awesome IM

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:37.440
client or messaging
client look like.

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:40.080
And so we came up with a few
screen mocks for what that

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:42.360
could look like.

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:44.180
We didn't give it a name or
anything, so it's just called

00:02:44.180 --> 00:02:46.090
hypothetical messaging app.

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:49.930
And you can see here this is
kind of one of the key Hero

00:02:49.930 --> 00:02:51.310
screens for the app.

00:02:51.310 --> 00:02:53.230
It's basically the conversation
view.

00:02:53.230 --> 00:02:55.440
In this view, you're
communicating with a bunch of

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:56.000
different people.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:57.370
In this case, you're
Luke Skywalker

00:02:57.370 --> 00:02:59.390
talking to all your friends.

00:02:59.390 --> 00:03:01.500
And the point here is that
we didn't want to really

00:03:01.500 --> 00:03:04.540
emphasize all the Chrome around
the instant messaging,

00:03:04.540 --> 00:03:07.210
like all the action bar stuff
and the action buttons that we

00:03:07.210 --> 00:03:08.550
talk about usually.

00:03:08.550 --> 00:03:11.940
We really wanted to focus on how
you present the content.

00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:15.220
So here you can notice that
there's three different types

00:03:15.220 --> 00:03:16.340
of content, really.

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:20.320
There's rich information about
a place that you've shared, a

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:25.620
rich kind of audio snippet with
transcribed text, and

00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:27.720
then a bunch of photos that
you've submitted.

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:30.600
So that's at a very basic
level what this

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:31.370
screen shows you.

00:03:31.370 --> 00:03:33.450
And it's really just a
conversation view.

00:03:33.450 --> 00:03:35.940
You guys have any preliminary
comments before we keep going?

00:03:38.690 --> 00:03:40.494
ADAM KOCH: No.

00:03:40.494 --> 00:03:42.120
I have something quick.

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:44.400
I just really like the fact
that there's rich content

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:46.150
included here directly.

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:48.360
I think we've moved beyond
having just text in instant

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:49.390
messaging clients.

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:51.390
And now we have phones, which
you can take pictures, you can

00:03:51.390 --> 00:03:52.810
record audio.

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:54.700
Obviously, sharing places
is very important.

00:03:54.700 --> 00:03:57.640
So I just really like how it's
sort of different content

00:03:57.640 --> 00:03:59.100
types are being brought
out here.

00:03:59.100 --> 00:04:00.640
ROMAN NURIK: And a lot
of this isn't new.

00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:02.790
Existing apps like GroupMe
already do this.

00:04:02.790 --> 00:04:05.580
So you can share your current
location or--

00:04:05.580 --> 00:04:07.972
actually, I don't know if you
can share a place, but I think

00:04:07.972 --> 00:04:10.190
you can check in with
Foursquare, for example.

00:04:10.190 --> 00:04:11.360
And you can also
share pictures.

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:13.840
So existing apps do this, but
what we'd really like to see

00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:15.560
is more and more apps
doing this.

00:04:15.560 --> 00:04:17.114
Because it's no longer,
like you said,

00:04:17.114 --> 00:04:18.329
Adam, about just text.

00:04:18.329 --> 00:04:22.050
You really want to share
content or objects.

00:04:22.050 --> 00:04:24.100
In the next screen, you'll
notice that when you touch the

00:04:24.100 --> 00:04:26.300
little attach icon on the bottom
left, you could be

00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:29.170
presented with things like
take a photo, record some

00:04:29.170 --> 00:04:32.410
audio, and then maybe
automatically transcribe it,

00:04:32.410 --> 00:04:34.990
and then obviously, attach
location, things like that.

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:37.130
One of the coolest things that
I really want instant

00:04:37.130 --> 00:04:39.040
messaging clients to start
thinking about

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:41.150
is streaming video.

00:04:41.150 --> 00:04:42.680
And this is kind of interesting
because you have

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:47.460
things like Google+ Hangouts
where you can basically create

00:04:47.460 --> 00:04:50.050
a shared meeting space with
your friends and with your

00:04:50.050 --> 00:04:53.140
family and all be on video
at the same time.

00:04:53.140 --> 00:04:56.160
But for some reason, I was
thinking about, like what

00:04:56.160 --> 00:04:57.320
about those push-to-talk days?

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:00.580
You know Sprint, Nextel, where
you'd push, say something, and

00:05:00.580 --> 00:05:02.320
everybody would hear
it streaming live.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:03.990
What if you could do
that with video?

00:05:03.990 --> 00:05:07.080
So I did a quick mockup.

00:05:07.080 --> 00:05:09.130
Let's just skip this one.

00:05:09.130 --> 00:05:13.850
I did a quick mockup of what
that could look like.

00:05:13.850 --> 00:05:17.295
I guess you press the attach
icon, and select stream video

00:05:17.295 --> 00:05:18.620
from your camera.

00:05:18.620 --> 00:05:22.760
It immediately changes the
compose box into basically a

00:05:22.760 --> 00:05:25.630
preview of your front-facing
camera.

00:05:25.630 --> 00:05:28.810
As you're talking, it's
streaming live in the stream

00:05:28.810 --> 00:05:30.760
of the conversation
to everybody else.

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:35.800
And then for you as the
recorder, you just see this

00:05:35.800 --> 00:05:37.690
live token in the stream.

00:05:37.690 --> 00:05:40.810
And then maybe as people are
saying stuff, as they are

00:05:40.810 --> 00:05:44.720
responding to your video, they
can type and type and type,

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:47.990
and it will maybe stick
your video feed to the

00:05:47.990 --> 00:05:49.440
top of their window.

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:51.190
That wasn't mocked
up, of course.

00:05:51.190 --> 00:05:52.630
ADAM KOCH: So just to be clear,
the video's actually

00:05:52.630 --> 00:05:54.310
playing in line in the
conversation with you, right?

00:05:54.310 --> 00:05:55.190
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:05:55.190 --> 00:05:55.950
ADAM KOCH: And would there
be like a full

00:05:55.950 --> 00:05:56.930
screen mode as well?

00:05:56.930 --> 00:05:57.700
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:05:57.700 --> 00:05:59.800
Yeah, so, I mean, we didn't
mock this up.

00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:01.900
I think if we had some more
time, we'd totally do this.

00:06:01.900 --> 00:06:04.320
But the idea would be like
you're streaming video.

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:06.030
It's not like--

00:06:06.030 --> 00:06:10.000
actually, it is recorded, so
after you press this check box

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.800
to indicate that you're done,
that video is just a token

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:15.840
that's playable, kind of like
a YouTube video or whatever

00:06:15.840 --> 00:06:17.140
that's attached.

00:06:17.140 --> 00:06:20.830
But in line, in the stream, if
somebody's currently streaming

00:06:20.830 --> 00:06:24.640
video, you can watch it in
line or full screen it.

00:06:24.640 --> 00:06:26.645
So this is something that I just
haven't seen other apps

00:06:26.645 --> 00:06:28.040
do, and I think that it's
something that--

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:31.540
like think about ways to compose
rich content, not only

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:32.815
view rich content,
but compose it.

00:06:36.770 --> 00:06:39.670
In another one of these
screenshots or mocks, you have

00:06:39.670 --> 00:06:42.530
this kind of composition window
that can accept tokens.

00:06:42.530 --> 00:06:44.910
So let's say you
paste the URL.

00:06:44.910 --> 00:06:47.790
What if you just paste the token
indicating that this is

00:06:47.790 --> 00:06:49.110
a URL object?

00:06:49.110 --> 00:06:53.770
And maybe a place is also kind
of like a place token or such.

00:06:53.770 --> 00:06:54.990
This is just something
that I think folks

00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:56.500
should think about.

00:06:56.500 --> 00:06:56.650
ADAM KOCH: Yeah, I think
it's cool because--

00:06:56.650 --> 00:06:59.115
NICK BUTCHER: Is the idea with
the images as well that you

00:06:59.115 --> 00:07:01.310
can scroll those in line?

00:07:01.310 --> 00:07:02.560
ROMAN NURIK: Yes.

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:05.400
Where is it?

00:07:05.400 --> 00:07:06.360
Let's go back here.

00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:09.890
If you have a set of six or
seven images that you've

00:07:09.890 --> 00:07:11.420
attached, then you
should probably

00:07:11.420 --> 00:07:12.840
support the share intent.

00:07:12.840 --> 00:07:15.310
So if I'm in Gallery, and I
select eight images, I should

00:07:15.310 --> 00:07:18.380
be able to share to my
messaging client.

00:07:18.380 --> 00:07:23.050
If I get a conversation or a
message, with eight images, I

00:07:23.050 --> 00:07:24.580
should be able to swipe
through them left

00:07:24.580 --> 00:07:26.850
and right in line.

00:07:26.850 --> 00:07:27.730
NICK BUTCHER: That's awesome.

00:07:27.730 --> 00:07:29.290
And yeah, with so many apps,
there's like a lot of--

00:07:29.290 --> 00:07:31.380
I guess you call it pogo
sticking, where you have to go

00:07:31.380 --> 00:07:33.090
up and down, in and
out, and have all

00:07:33.090 --> 00:07:34.170
these context switches.

00:07:34.170 --> 00:07:37.010
So I love the idea of staying
within a fluent conversation

00:07:37.010 --> 00:07:39.403
but being able to take in
all the immediate types.

00:07:39.403 --> 00:07:40.090
It's cool.

00:07:40.090 --> 00:07:41.490
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, and this is
something that the Gmail

00:07:41.490 --> 00:07:44.480
recently did with the
Android 4.2 update.

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:49.360
Gmail now lets you have this
mini-Gallery view within an

00:07:49.360 --> 00:07:49.970
email message.

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:52.880
So if you get an email message
with 10 attachments, you don't

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:55.480
have to jump in to see
each individual one.

00:07:55.480 --> 00:07:59.370
You basically have a
horizontally swipeable gallery

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:04.080
for the email messages of the
attachments that were there.

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:06.760
So rather than spend too much
time on instant messaging,

00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:09.470
again the main event
is coming up.

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:14.180
The last thing I just want to
talk about is the tablet UI

00:08:14.180 --> 00:08:14.920
that we designed here.

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:19.060
So again, this is fairly
standard, a very simple master

00:08:19.060 --> 00:08:22.890
detailed view, where on the
left, you have a master list

00:08:22.890 --> 00:08:27.410
of all your conversations, and
then on the right, you have

00:08:27.410 --> 00:08:29.220
your conversation view.

00:08:29.220 --> 00:08:31.670
The important thing to note
here, and this is where the

00:08:31.670 --> 00:08:34.380
interesting part of tablets
comes in, is there's a lot of

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:37.110
ways to optimize for a tablet.

00:08:37.110 --> 00:08:40.250
On the left, obviously, we're
combining screens.

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:42.179
But on the right, you'll notice
that the presentation

00:08:42.179 --> 00:08:45.280
of the conversation itself
is slightly different.

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:49.750
We've increased the padding,
the spacing, the margins to

00:08:49.750 --> 00:08:54.360
let the core content float
freely within your bounds so

00:08:54.360 --> 00:08:57.390
that it's not compressed into
one of the corners and edges.

00:08:57.390 --> 00:09:01.630
So the spacing between the
conversation and the avatar is

00:09:01.630 --> 00:09:06.760
increased, between the avatar
and the side of the screen.

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:08.270
And then everything
is just bigger.

00:09:08.270 --> 00:09:11.100
These images are no longer a
one-to-one aspect ratio.

00:09:11.100 --> 00:09:14.790
They're slightly wider to,
again, account for the extra

00:09:14.790 --> 00:09:16.780
width you have on that screen.

00:09:16.780 --> 00:09:18.630
And then everything is larger.

00:09:18.630 --> 00:09:25.380
So this composition bar
at the bottom is--

00:09:25.380 --> 00:09:27.740
I forgot the exact dimensions it
shows, but it was about one

00:09:27.740 --> 00:09:30.880
and a half to two times as tall
for a much larger, more

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:32.570
accessible touch target.

00:09:32.570 --> 00:09:35.710
And then at the very top, this
presence bar that shows you

00:09:35.710 --> 00:09:37.560
all the people that are
currently viewing the

00:09:37.560 --> 00:09:39.970
conversation as well as all the
people that are involved

00:09:39.970 --> 00:09:42.610
in the conversation, that's also
slightly larger to give

00:09:42.610 --> 00:09:46.110
the thumbnails more
space to breathe.

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:48.690
So that's kind of just one
example of how you could take

00:09:48.690 --> 00:09:52.400
something as simple as a list of
messages and turn it into a

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:54.250
great tablet UI.

00:09:54.250 --> 00:09:57.260
Before we jump into our main
event talking about all the

00:09:57.260 --> 00:09:59.220
awesome stuff that the community
has done, anything

00:09:59.220 --> 00:10:01.290
else you guys want to talk
about in terms of IM and

00:10:01.290 --> 00:10:02.540
messaging clients?

00:10:05.300 --> 00:10:07.400
ADAM KOCH: I guess one thing I
wanted to mention was there's

00:10:07.400 --> 00:10:11.850
a lot of popular IM clients out
there on the Play Store.

00:10:11.850 --> 00:10:14.790
But for some reason, the most
popular ones typically do a

00:10:14.790 --> 00:10:19.290
pretty poor job at the actual
presentation and design, maybe

00:10:19.290 --> 00:10:21.140
because they've been around for
a long time, maybe because

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:22.580
they focus more on the
functionality.

00:10:22.580 --> 00:10:26.630
I'm not sure, but personally,
I'd really love a client that

00:10:26.630 --> 00:10:30.890
just had a great design and
worked really, really well,

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:32.380
like this, for example.

00:10:32.380 --> 00:10:34.980
ROMAN NURIK: I think also just
on top of that, just getting

00:10:34.980 --> 00:10:39.480
the details right, making sure
notifications work, making

00:10:39.480 --> 00:10:43.060
sure things are quick, that
you never miss anything.

00:10:43.060 --> 00:10:43.730
That's also important.

00:10:43.730 --> 00:10:46.580
But on top of that, to go
above and beyond your

00:10:46.580 --> 00:10:51.180
competition, having a great
tablet UI and having a strong

00:10:51.180 --> 00:10:54.160
visual presentation of the
content itself, of the

00:10:54.160 --> 00:10:56.930
messages and your friends that
you're talking with, that's

00:10:56.930 --> 00:11:00.160
going to put you above
and beyond.

