00:23:58.160 --> 00:23:59.840
IMDb.

00:23:59.840 --> 00:24:02.570
Nick, do you want to
talk about IMDb?

00:24:02.570 --> 00:24:04.420
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah,
absolutely.

00:24:04.420 --> 00:24:06.770
What I really liked about this
redesign, in particular, was

00:24:06.770 --> 00:24:11.090
they didn't only apply a Holo
look and feel to it.

00:24:11.090 --> 00:24:14.490
They also took a stab at looking
at the information

00:24:14.490 --> 00:24:14.930
architecture.

00:24:14.930 --> 00:24:16.190
So when I say they,
it's Paul Burke.

00:24:16.190 --> 00:24:17.490
Good job, Paul.

00:24:17.490 --> 00:24:21.320
He looked at the way that
people, he and his friends, he

00:24:21.320 --> 00:24:22.350
says, use IMDb.

00:24:22.350 --> 00:24:24.300
And it definitely resonated
with me, that you're quite

00:24:24.300 --> 00:24:26.750
often using mobile in a
different context than you are

00:24:26.750 --> 00:24:27.530
using a website.

00:24:27.530 --> 00:24:31.530
And he's really rearranged the
hierarchy of the information

00:24:31.530 --> 00:24:33.640
to make things, like you know,
you're watching a movie.

00:24:33.640 --> 00:24:36.170
You want to see who the actor
is or what other movies

00:24:36.170 --> 00:24:38.580
they've been in and make that
really, really quick.

00:24:38.580 --> 00:24:41.000
And he's used images really
well, I think, throughout the

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:44.610
app to make it very quick to
see what's going on and

00:24:44.610 --> 00:24:47.960
visually you kind of
like pause the app.

00:24:47.960 --> 00:24:50.000
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, and you
can't see this here.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:53.010
In one of his mockups, he
basically hid all the trivia

00:24:53.010 --> 00:24:56.220
information, like the birth date
and so on for the actor,

00:24:56.220 --> 00:24:59.680
hid that under an expandable
item here at the top.

00:24:59.680 --> 00:25:04.130
And it's nice to be able to
focus on the stuff that you

00:25:04.130 --> 00:25:05.380
immediately want to
see on mobile.

00:25:05.380 --> 00:25:06.660
I mean, you probably
want to see, oh my

00:25:06.660 --> 00:25:07.740
god, I just saw somebody.

00:25:07.740 --> 00:25:09.870
Is that Joseph Gordon-Levitt?

00:25:09.870 --> 00:25:13.110
You want to be able to tell
by looking at some photos.

00:25:13.110 --> 00:25:16.350
Maybe you're not as interested
about when they were born or

00:25:16.350 --> 00:25:19.000
where they grew up or
something on the go.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.550
So definitely a good rethinking
of the entire

00:25:21.550 --> 00:25:25.100
experience on mobile of what is
the user trying to get at.

00:25:25.100 --> 00:25:27.990
And then when you touch on one
of these movie titles, it

00:25:27.990 --> 00:25:29.970
gives you a very quick pop-up.

00:25:29.970 --> 00:25:31.490
I'd probably use something
beside a pop-up.

00:25:31.490 --> 00:25:33.960
But it shows you a very quick
pop-up showing you the

00:25:33.960 --> 00:25:36.900
immediately important things
like the rating and then I

00:25:36.900 --> 00:25:38.650
think the metascore.

00:25:38.650 --> 00:25:43.660
So obviously, you want to see if
movies are good on the go.

00:25:43.660 --> 00:25:46.980
You're deciding between
something, so making that

00:25:46.980 --> 00:25:51.125
rating, number, or star meter
or whatever really prominent

00:25:51.125 --> 00:25:52.810
is probably pretty important.

00:25:52.810 --> 00:25:54.410
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah, generally
a dialogue's not the answer.

00:25:54.410 --> 00:25:57.320
But I'd quite like to see that
perhaps as another expand in

00:25:57.320 --> 00:25:59.600
place, a bit like
he has for the

00:25:59.600 --> 00:26:00.498
information about the actor.

00:26:00.498 --> 00:26:02.640
That could be quite fun.

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:02.970
ROMAN NURIK: OK.

